-- South African Stocks Climb for Second Day, Led by Billiton, Anglo American
-- Nicky Smith
-- 2010-07-21T16:22:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-21/south-african-stocks-climb-for-a-second-day-led-by-avi-pioneer-simmers.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  gained for a second day, adding 483.91, or 1.8
percent, to 27,833.52 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  
 The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  
 AVI Ltd.  (AVI SJ), a South African food producer, advanced
for a second day, gaining 25 cents, or 1.1 percent, to 24.15
rand. Morgan Stanley upgraded the stock to “overweight” from
“equal weight” and increased its price estimate to 26 rand
from 24.50 rand.  
 BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, rose 5.39 rand, or 2.5 percent, to 220 rand. Copper for
three-month delivery in London climbed for a third day, rising
as much as 2.9 percent as London Metal Exchange copper
stockpiles fell for a 24th day today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL
SJ), the mining company that makes up almost 10 percent of South
Africa’s benchmark index, rose 1.5 percent to 278 rand.  
 Pioneer Foods Ltd.  (PFG SJ), the South African maker of
Sasko bread and Weet-Bix cereal, rallied 50 cents, or 1.2
percent, to 41.50 rand. Morgan Stanley raised the stock to
“equal weight” from “underweight” and increased its price
estimate to 45 rand from 40.50 rand.  
 Sasol Ltd. (SOL SJ), the world’s largest maker of
automotive fuel from coal, advanced 7.58 rand, or 2.7 percent to
287.98 rand. Crude oil rose as much as 1.5 percent to $78.57 a
barrel in New York. Sasol said its antitrust settlement
agreement “will not have a material adverse financial impact”
on the company.  
 Simmer & Jack Mines Ltd.  (SIM SJ), a gold mining company,
rose for a second day, adding 18 cents, or 22 percent, to 1
rand. The Department of Mineral Resources transferred the mining
rights for the Tau Lekoa mine to its Buffelsfontein Gold Mines
Ltd. unit from AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  
 Tiger Brands Ltd.  (TBS SJ), South Africa’s largest food
company, gained for a second day, climbing 3.74 rand, or 2.1
percent, to 180.50 rand. Morgan Stanley upgraded the stock to
“overweight” from “equal weight” and raised its price
estimate to 200 rand from 193 rand.  
